 from the same modern developments—industrialization, consumerism—typically believed to constrain human freedom. With Women, Compulsion, and Modernity, Fleissner creates a new language for the strange way the writings of the time both broaden and question individual agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFeminism and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFeminist fiction, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aNaturalism in literature. 0aSex role in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aamerica, american, united states, usa, naturalist, naturalism, history, historical, time period, era, womens issues, modern, contemporary, 1800s, 19th century, english major, classroom, textbook, frank norris, literary analysis, literature, mary wilkins freeman, charlotte perkins gilman, stephen crane, feminism, industrialization, consumerism, freedom, agency, rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226805764423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226805764/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles